SIMPLE: countersign
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Countersign
<hw>Coun`ter*sign"</hw> <pr>(-s?n`; 277)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Countersigned</conjf>
<pr>(-s?nd`)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Countersigning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[<ets>Counter-</ets> +
<ets>sign</ets>: cf. F. <ets>contresigner</ets>.]</ety> <def>To sign on
the opposite side of (an instrument or writing); hence, to sign in
addition to the signature of a principal or superior, in order to attest
the authenticity of a writing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Countersign</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Countersign
<hw>Coun"ter*sign`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The signature of
a secretary or other officer to a writing signed by a principal or
superior, to attest its authenticity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A private signal, word, or phrase,
which must be given in order to pass a sentry; a watchword.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>countersignature</ent>⟦br⟧
